<br>
Maybe I'm just too big a believer in history repeating itself, but I see a distubing trend, and one that I'm none to pleased about. I'm starting to think that complacency will be the death of the free American state. <p>Lauriston Pianoforte<br>That Guy<br>Bard of Quellious</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/ubulvaihammersson.showPublicProfile?language=EN>BulvaiHammersson</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Froglok Dar Knight</span><br>  Posts: 136<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(8/3/02 7:11:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=445.topic&index=63>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: political rant: /sigh bush</span><hr size=1> &quot;That's a bit different. Our normal military, except in the event of martial law or insurrection, cannot be mobilized against its people. Also, he has extremely limited powers as far as the military is concerned; I believe the president has the ability to deploy them for up to 10 days before asking Congress to declare war.&quot; <br>
<br>
My father served in the US Army for 24 years. During the Chicago riots back in the 60's, he was in the 82nd Airborne Div (and served in that div numerous times as he liked jumping out of perfectly good airplanes). They mobilised the 82nd to quell that riot. For about 3 weeks you had soldier, hard-core shooters from the 82nd, marching down Chicago streets with loaded rifles. Sounds like a police state nightmare, but no civilians were hurt/killed and the riots stopped dead.<br>
<br>
Am I advocating such use of the military, not particularly. It did work though.<br>
<br>
As far as mobilising that military against the people, I'm not the best person to ask, but what I recall from Constitutional Law courses was that the statute regarding military deployment and the office of the president are fairly muddled. Arlen Specter is currently sponsoring a bill specifically designed to prevent the president from making war without the assent of congress. Specter would not be sponsoring this bill if he did not think the law was open to Bush making war without congress' go-ahead.<br>
<br>
&quot;And if you can neither see where this is going or coming from, I beg you to take a closer look. Since the HSA will technically be counted as a military agency, with jurisdiction over the interior, they will in essence be an undeployable multi-capability unit. If the old law gets overturned, they will have the right to arrest you anything they want to. Yes, the military now can arrest you if you commit a felonius act on their territory, but they cannot arrest you for jaywalking. If this law is overturned, the HSA can. And they can hold you indefinetly.&quot;<br>
<br>
I'm not sure I see this. The HSA is military? Are they under the Dept of Defense? I admit to not keeping that close a tabs on the recent changes, but I thought they were associated directly with the office of the President in the Organisational Charts. This would mean they had similar status to the CIA and such agencies. From what I've seen, that HSA will not need the power of arrest in itself. It can simply turn over what info it has to agencies like the FBI and they'll arrest. Again, I've not kept up on recent changes.<br>
<br>
I do see what you are saying here, but I still think that it is a touch early in the game to be this alarmist. It does scare me a bit. I am, as I've said before, a conservative and Libertarian, and I dislike the feds having any more power than they've already got. My idea for the HSA was a simple clearinghouse of data, allowing inter-agency communication. It is apparently becoming much more than that, both from what I've seen and what you are saying. Still, I cannot see it, just yet, as jack-booted thugs. That would too closely infringe on the BATF's charter =)<br>
<br>
&quot;Hitler didn't start out as a cackling, mass-murdering fuckhead. If he did, he wouldn't have gotten elected (yes, Germany was Democratic then). He revitalized the German economy, made overtures to those countries to which Germany owed money, and then took advantage of the complaceny of the world powers to gather his own power base and launch a devastating global war.&quot;<br>
<br>
Yes, Hitler was democratically elected. Heck, he was Time's Man of the Year at one point. He started out as a Good Thing for Germany. The problem here is the lack of proportion in your argument/analogy. Germany was devastated by WWI, and the agreements that were forced on them were utterly emasculating. Were we not involved in that war, a better balance of power would've been achieved and Germany would not have needed the Little Corporal. This is another argument though.<br>
<br>
America is NOT in the same boat that Germany was in. You don't have currency so devalued that you need a wheelbarrow to carry enough money to buy bread. You don't have infrastructure so poor that it is easier to walk to the next town to buy supplies than it is to wait for the delivery to your local store. You don't have an utterly crushing disarmament of the nation. There is a major problem of scope here. America is nothing like post-WWI Germany in scope.<br>
<br>
&quot;I see Bush attempting to revitalize the US economy.&quot;<br>
<br>
Every leader of every nation with a flagging economy tries to do the same. Anything else is political suicide. Again, I ask what is wrong with this?<br>
<br>
&quot;I see Bush taking advantage of 9/11 to gather power to himself and make war on those countries that he doesn't like.&quot;<br>
<br>
Well, agree and disagree. I see the steps he is taking garners more power for the govt, not necessarily himself, though it can be argued that strengthening the govt strenghtens the president. I do not see him using it as an excuse to make war on countries he doesn't like. We didn't give two shits about Afghanistan before this, and, as I've said before, I see no evidence of a war in Iraq at all.<br>
<br>
&quot;I see Bush, during some near-future crisis, being declared pro-temp Supreme Leader (or maybe not, something similar to what happened with Johnson during Vietnam will suffice) and making war on the Middle East, which will lead us to devastaing global war.&quot;<br>
<br>
Wow, this isn't a leap of whimsy, this is an around-the-world-tour of whimsy! How did we get from &quot;Bush is trying to revitalize the economy&quot; to &quot;W, Supreme Secretary, World Govt&quot;? Is this like those descriptions of FTL Drives in sci-fi books that include the step &quot;And a miricale happens here&quot;?<br>
<br>
&quot;Where perhaps I went wrong in likening Bush to Hitler was genocide. I don't think Bush will do anything quite so organized as that. What I fear will happen is the painting of the biggest thorns as terrorist sympathizers, which we all know is treason, punishable by death. Nevermind the small thorns in our conquered empire-puppet states, who won't even make the front page.&quot;<br>
<br>
Actually, no one has been seriously tried for treason, and I doubt it'll happen. Treason is a n offense punishable by death. The feds are loathe to pull out that power due to world attention. It's apparently ok for Texas to execute a serial killer, but the world media would probably have a field day if the US executed a Traitor.<br>
<br>
Another problem here is that our biggest thorns are terrorist sympathizers. <br>
<br>
&quot;Maybe I'm just too big a believer in history repeating itself, but I see a distubing trend, and one that I'm none to pleased about. I'm starting to think that complacency will be the death of the free American state.&quot;<br>
<br>
Some of the indicators are there, but I stil think that your sense of history is ignoring your sense of proportion. History does repeat itself, but Americans of today are a far cry from thee wrecked shell of a people that populated Germany post-WWI. Bush is nowhere near as charismatic as Hitler. And there is no Nevillle Chamberlain on the other side. I think Tony Blair would be the first to stand up and call Bush on the carpet if he started to turn into the Little Corporal.<br>
<br>
Still, we aren't on opposite sides of the fence here, Lauriston. I am fond of the phrase, &quot;I love my country, but I fear my government&quot;. I think we need to keep tabs on what our govt is doing. I just think that, in spots, you've gone far afield in your comparisons. <p>a_Bearhat01<BR>
