&quot;My point above was not that the lesson Europe learned during WW2 was that it must stop fascist aggressors, but that it must seek a way to interact with each other other than military force and nationalistic pride. European countries had to learn how not to agitate each other and &quot;contain&quot; each other through use of force. They now contain each other through treaties and diplomacy. But you don't do modern diplomacy and treaties by stationing troops and provoking &quot;regime changes&quot;. That is pre-world war thinking.&quot;<br>
<br>
America pulls it troops out of an area that hasn't finished pulling itself into the modern world. That area degenrates into violence, chaos, and despair. Panama and the Phillipines are both examples of this. <br>
<br>
America leaves it's troops in place in numerous European countries because those countries want us there. We also happen to have bases owned by foreign powers herein the States now too. There is at least one German Luftwaffe base that I can think of in New Mexico or Arizona. It's a grand idea.<br>
<br>
Regime changes are attempted when the rulers of a nation prove that they are not mature enough to handle the power. You are a self-professed peacenik, yet you'd rather see Saddam Hussein in power than not? While I do not advocate war with Iraq, I do advocate a regime change, especially in a rogue state like Iraq.<br>
<br>
As far as containement through treaty, containment works when the nation being treated with is willing to respond to reason. Did we not try damned hard to bring accord through treaty and diplomacy in both Iraq and with the Palestinians? Admittedly, little diplomacy was attempted with Afghanistan, but there wasn't much of a govt to be diplomatic with.<br>
<br>
&quot;The US is basically 100 years behind European nations in terms of understanding how to be a modern nation in terms of dealing with other nations.&quot;<br>
<br>
Well, I somehow don't see this, as we aren't exactly practising Battleship Diplomacy as was de riguer in the early 1900's Crazy, but true, we aren't taking our Navy and Army into lesser developed countries to rape them of their resources and establish puppet governments. We allow our private corporations to do that.<br>
<br>
&quot;There are other issues as well; we could talk about the insanity of trying to teach people that using violence to solve problems is unacceptable by putting people who use violence to solve problems to death. (The death penalty **reinforces** the violent criminal's tendency to think wrongs deserve violent reactions. Murderers who kill people for &quot;disrespecting&quot; them are, in other words, simply following the lesson taught by the death penalty)&quot;<br>
<br>
This is simply inane. The death penalty has been discussed and debated forever and a day now. It has been shown to be economically inefficient, it has been shown statistically inefficient, it has been shown to be statistically efficient, it has been shown to do everything but jump up and dance. The bottom line is that some offenses are so grave as to only be assuaged by one measure, and a measure most final it is. There are those so removed from humanity as to be no longer human. They should thus be treated accordingly in the very end. To do less is to show deep moral weakness to the rest of society, so deeply damaged by such diabolical actions.<br>
<br>
Our penal system is horribly broken nowadays, much of this is due to overly compassionate folks, probably like yourself, that have overemphasized the &quot;correct&quot; in corrections. Felons today are punished primarily by their fellows via &quot;jailhouse justice&quot;. It is no wonder that our recidivism rate is so damned high, given how essentially soft our prison system is.<br>
<br>
&quot;And I still stay by my point. Europe is more wary of war because they have seen it happen in their own lands. WW1 and WW2 were devastating ordeals for Europe. The US only sees war on TV. And then, when terrorists destroy 4,000 or so American lives on American soil, we have the naivete to recoil in horror as if the world has never seen such atrocity before. Sure it has. Every year. All over the place. It's just that we Americans only see it on TV.&quot;<br>
<br>
This is inane. Please point out any other instance in history where so many people in one nation have been murdered in one instant in such a brutal, unexpected, and unexplained fashion. Certainly massacres have occurred in many nations, but I cannot think of another example when it was so many, so unexpected, so well televised, and so instantaneous.<br>
<br>
You did not recoil in horror? What kind of person are you? I am unashamed to say thatm by your definition, I am naive as I certainly felt deeply the horror of that event. It is probably unfortunate for me, by your viewpoint, that I am not as internationalist and as jaded to the suffering of the world. It is surely better to be like you and not feel the outrage that so many of us feel at this act.<br>
<br>
I have quite a few British friends. They've suffered through the Blitzkrieg and the Battle of Britain etc, yet they recoiled in horror at the events that day. Are they naive too?<br>
<br>
&quot;But that's ok. Because America is gonna teach the world how to be free! We are freedom! We are moral truth! And we have God on our side....&quot;<br>
<br>
Please. Do you still live here? Do you pay taxes and accept govt support, drive on govt roads? Have you expatriated yourself yet to some bastion of true freedom like, oh, Cuba? All I see, is the same parlor dissident BS, bitching diffidently about how awful America is whilest sipping on a latte.<br>
<br>
I have yet to see an alternative. Those nations that are generally held up as better examples of freedom either oppress far worse than we see here, or simply have succumbed to anarchy and freedom of self-expression occurs only because you have troops backing your voice.<br>
<br>
&quot;And let me add one more thing. It is one of the most difficult things a person or people can do to come to an awareness that their homeland, their country, their nation, is not all peachy-keen. Maybe THIS is what WE need to learn from WW2. The Germans could not face up to the fact: our nation is horribly and utterly corrupt and wrong.&quot;<br>
<br>
It's not difficult in the slightest! Every year on April 15th, I am confronted again with how wrong some things are in the system. Everytime I see the latest numbers on how much money is being wasted on crap like the welfare slave-mill, everytime I see yet another piece of trash lawsuit that is as pointless as the day is long. The difference between you and I is that I also see the good. I have been to other nations, seen truly corupt regimes in actions. I know what the alternative is. There is bad here, but there is also a helluva lot of good. I feel sorry for those who can't see it.<br>
<br>
&quot;Sometimes the most blessedly patriotic thing a man can do is recognize his dear country has big problems. Its a lot like recognizing maybe your parents are not perfect wise beings. Time to grow up kiddies.&quot;<br>
<br>
The most blessedly patriotic thing you can do right now is to just go out and be a normal, law-abiding citizen. That is the best way to supprot your nation, economy, and fellow man. There is nothing patriotic or unpatriotic about realizing that this and every nation has problems. It is simply recognizing reality as it stands.<br>
<br>
